### 1. Brief Summary of the Facts  
The case concerns a dispute over the validity of two wills following the death of **Nina Wang**, a billionaire businesswoman, in 2007. The **Chinachem Charitable Foundation Ltd** (the Foundation), as the beneficiary under **Mrs. Wang’s 2002 will**, sought a court declaration confirming its validity and challenging the authenticity of an **alleged 2006 will** propounded by the **Applicant, Chan Chun Chuen**, who claimed sole entitlement to the entire estate. After a 40-day trial, **Justice Lam** ruled the 2006 will was a **forgery**, and the **Court of Appeal** upheld this finding. The Applicant now seeks **leave to appeal** to the **Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal** (CFA) under **section 22(1) of the Court of Final Appeal Ordinance**, arguing:  
- **As of right** under section 22(1)(a) (claim exceeding $1 million in value);  
- **Discretionary leave** under section 22(1)(b) (question of public importance or "otherwise").  
The Foundation opposed the application, arguing the appeal fails to meet the statutory thresholds. The CFA dismissed the application, holding the appeal did not qualify for leave as of right due to the **lack of immediacy** in financial impact and rejecting all discretionary grounds. The court also **criticized the "as of right" appeal regime** as outdated, urging its abolition.  

